texts.label: text
texts.orig: Under section 3 of the Act on the Ice Classes of Ships and Icebreaker Assistance (1121/2005), ships are assigned to ice classes as follows:
texts.text: Under section 3 of the Act on the Ice Classes of Ships and Icebreaker Assistance (1121/2005), ships are assigned to ice classes as follows:

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 1. ice class IA Super; ships with such a structure, engine output and other properties that they are normally capable of navigating in difficult ice conditions without the assistance of icebreakers;
texts.text: ice class IA Super; ships with such a structure, engine output and other properties that they are normally capable of navigating in difficult ice conditions without the assistance of icebreakers;

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 2. ice class IA; ships with such a structure, engine output and other properties that they are capable of navigating in difficult ice conditions, with the assistance of icebreakers when necessary;
texts.text: ice class IA; ships with such a structure, engine output and other properties that they are capable of navigating in difficult ice conditions, with the assistance of icebreakers when necessary;

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 3. ice class IB; ships with such a structure, engine output and other properties that they are capable of navigating in moderate ice conditions, with the assistance of icebreakers when necessary;
texts.text: ice class IB; ships with such a structure, engine output and other properties that they are capable of navigating in moderate ice conditions, with the assistance of icebreakers when necessary;

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 4. ice class IC; ships with such a structure, engine output and other properties that they are capable of navigating in light ice conditions, with the assistance of icebreakers when necessary;
texts.text: ice class IC; ships with such a structure, engine output and other properties that they are capable of navigating in light ice conditions, with the assistance of icebreakers when necessary;

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 5. ice class II; ships that have a steel hull and that are structurally fit for navigation in the open sea and that, despite not being strengthened for navigation in ice, are capable of navigating in very light ice conditions using their own propulsion machinery;
texts.text: ice class II; ships that have a steel hull and that are structurally fit for navigation in the open sea and that, despite not being strengthened for navigation in ice, are capable of navigating in very light ice conditions using their own propulsion machinery;

texts.label: list_item
texts.orig: 6. ice class III; ships that do not belong to the ice classes referred to in paragraphs 1-5.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: 2.1 Upper and lower ice waterlines
texts.text: 2.1 Upper and lower ice waterlines

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The upper ice waterline (UIWL) shall be the envelope of the highest points of the waterlines at which the ship is intended to operate in ice. The line may be a broken line.
texts.text: The upper ice waterline (UIWL) shall be the envelope of the highest points of the waterlines at which the ship is intended to operate in ice. The line may be a broken line.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The lower ice waterline (LIWL) shall be the envelope of the lowest points of the waterlines at which the ship is intended to operate in ice. The line may be a broken line.
texts.text: The lower ice waterline (LIWL) shall be the envelope of the lowest points of the waterlines at which the ship is intended to operate in ice. The line may be a broken line.

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: 2.2 Maximum and minimum draught fore and aft
texts.text: 2.2 Maximum and minimum draught fore and aft

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The maximum and minimum ice class draughts at fore and aft perpendiculars shall be determined in accordance with the upper and lower ice waterlines and the draught of the ship at fore and aft perpendiculars, when ice conditions require the ship to be ice-strengthened, shall always be between the upper and lower ice waterlines.
texts.text: The maximum and minimum ice class draughts at fore and aft perpendiculars shall be determined in accordance with the upper and lower ice waterlines and the draught of the ship at fore and aft perpendiculars, when ice conditions require the ship to be ice-strengthened, shall always be between the upper and lower ice waterlines.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: Restrictions on draughts when operating in ice shall be documented and kept on board readily available to the master. The maximum and minimum ice class draughts fore, amidships and aft shall be indicated in the class certificate. For ships built on or after 1 July 2007, if the summer load line in fresh water is anywhere located at a higher level than the UIWL, the ship's sides are to be provided with a warning triangle and with an ice class draught mark at the maximum permissible ice class draught amidships (see Annex III). Ships built before 1 July 2007 shall be provided with such a marking, if the UIWL is below the summer load line, not later than the first scheduled dry docking after 1 July 2007.
texts.text: Restrictions on draughts when operating in ice shall be documented and kept on board readily available to the master. The maximum and minimum ice class draughts fore, amidships and aft shall be indicated in the class certificate. For ships built on or after 1 July 2007, if the summer load line in fresh water is anywhere located at a higher level than the UIWL, the ship's sides are to be provided with a warning triangle and with an ice class draught mark at the maximum permissible ice class draught amidships (see Annex III). Ships built before 1 July 2007 shall be provided with such a marking, if the UIWL is below the summer load line, not later than the first scheduled dry docking after 1 July 2007.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The draught and trim, limited by the UIWL, must not be exceeded when the ship is navigating in ice. The salinity of the sea water along the intended route shall be taken into account when loading the ship.
texts.text: The draught and trim, limited by the UIWL, must not be exceeded when the ship is navigating in ice. The salinity of the sea water along the intended route shall be taken into account when loading the ship.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The ship shall always be loaded down at least to the draught of LIWL amidships when navigating in ice. Any ballast tank, situated above the LIWL and needed to load down the ship to this water line, shall be equipped with devices to prevent the water from freezing. In determining the LIWL, regard shall be paid to the need to ensure a reasonable degree of ice-going capability in ballast. The highest point of the propeller shall be submerged and if possible at a depth of at least hi below the water surface in all loading conditions. The forward draught shall be at least:

texts.label: section_header
texts.orig: 3.1 Definition of engine output
texts.text: 3.1 Definition of engine output

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The engine output P is the total maximum output the propulsion machinery can continuously deliver to the propeller(s). If the output of the machinery is restricted by technical means or by any regulations applicable to the ship, P shall be taken as the restricted output. If additional power sources are available for propulsion power (e.g. shaft motors), in addition to the power of the main engine(s), they shall also be included in the total engine output.
texts.text: The engine output P is the total maximum output the propulsion machinery can continuously deliver to the propeller(s). If the output of the machinery is restricted by technical means or by any regulations applicable to the ship, P shall be taken as the restricted output. If additional power sources are available for propulsion power (e.g. shaft motors), in addition to the power of the main engine(s), they shall also be included in the total engine output.

texts.label: text
texts.orig: The method for determining hull scantlings is based on certain assumptions concerning the nature of the ice load on the structure. These assumptions are based on full-scale observations made in the northern Baltic.
